–1563":"1514–1563","1529–1565":"1529–1565","1536–1606":"1536–1606","1480–1523":"1480–1523","1480–1506":"1480–1506","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1536":"1536","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1557":"1557","1502":"1502","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","about 1528":"circa 1528","1620":"1620","1565":"1565","about 1501":"circa 1501","1563":"1563","about 1502":"circa 1502","1529":"1529","1606":"1606","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Euston, Suffolk, England":"Euston, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1502–":"about 1502–Deceased","1502–Male":"1502–Deceased","1504–1557":"1504–1557","1514–1563":"1514–1563","1529–1565":"1529–1565","1536–1606":"1536–1606","1480–1523":"1480–1523","1480–1506":"1480–1506","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1536":"1536","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1557":"1557","1502":"1502","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","about 1528":"about 1528","1620":"1620","1565":"1565","about 1501":"about 1501","1563":"1563","about 1502":"about 1502","1529":"1529","1606":"1606","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Euston, Suffolk, England":"Euston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rookwood","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places in Essex and Sussex named in Middle English with <i>rok(e)</i> ‘rook’ + <i>wod(e)</i> ‘wood’ (Old English <i>hrōc</i>, <i>wudu</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":47,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":56,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":67,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":69,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":98,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":118,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Rookwood Esq. was born about 1502, in Euston, Suffolk, England, his father, Edmund Rookwood Esquire, was 11500 and his mother, Mrs. Edmund Rookwood, was 24. He married Olivia Wichingham about 1528, in Euston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1502–":"umbes 1502–Surnud","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","1504–1557":"1504–1557","1514–1563":"1514–1563","1529–1565":"1529–1565","1536–1606":"1536–1606","1480–1523":"1480–1523","1480–1506":"1480–1506","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1536":"1536","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1557":"1557","1502":"1502","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","about 1528":"umbes 1528","1620":"1620","1565":"1565","about 1501":"umbes 1501","1563":"1563","abou